What is libvirt
Libvirt is a toolkit to manage virtualization platforms.
What libvirt can do

Manage virtualization hypervisors: 
QEMU/KVM, 
Xen, 
Virtuozzo, 
OpenVZ, 
VMWare ESX, 
VMware Workstation/Player/Fusion, 
VirtualBox, 
LXC, 
BHyve, 
IBM PowerVM, 
Microsoft Hyper-V
Manage host resources: 
storages, 
networks, 
host node devices, 
network filters, 
host interfaces

Preparation to review the code
Download the code
Use git to download libvirt source code.  
git clone git://libvirt.org/libvirt.git

Learn git
Git is powerful version-control system for tracking changes in source code. 
The following git sub-commands are useful for browsing the code.
git log
Git log is to show the commits history of the source code.Run it directly in the source code directory then get the commits from the last to the first:
git log

By format strings, you can set the format of commits log. This link 
gives the full format or git log.
For example, see the commit hash, author, author date, commit subject:
git log --pretty="format:%H %an %aD %s"

And it can get the commits from one to another:
git log COMMIT1..COMMIT2

By using tags, you can find the commits during two versions. For example, the 
following command will show the commits between version v4.5.0 to v4.6.0 :
git log v4.5.0..v4.6.0

Man page: git log
git tag
Tags are ref's that point to specific points in Git history.  Tagging is generally 
used to capture a point in history that is used for a marked version release (i.e. v1.0.1).Run as following in source code dir to show all the tags:
git tag

--contains is to show which tags contains a specific commit:
git tag --contains COMMIT

Man page: git tag
git show
Git show can check the detailed changes of commits.To show the latest code change of a commit:
git show

Show code change of specific commit:
Man page: git show
vim plugins
fugitive.vim
fugitive.vim is a nice git wrapper of vim.You can use pathogen.vim or Vundle.vim
 to install it.See chapter Practice, how to use vim&git to find which software versions contain 
the code of a specific line.

How to build libvirt

Install dependencies

For Fedora/Centos
For Debian/Ubuntu

Download the code
Configuration
Make
Installation
Build by build system of distributions




How to build libvirt
Install dependencies
Make source repository is configurated.  
For Fedora/Centos
Install dependencies via dnf builddep:
dnf builddep libvirt -y

For earlier fedora/centos, install yum-utils first and then install 
dependencies via yum-builddep:
yum install yum-utils -y && yum-builddep libvirt -y

For Debian/Ubuntu
Install dependencies by apt build-dep:
apt build-dep libvirt0 -y

Download the code
According to libvirt download page, 
download your preferred libvirt version at https://libvirt.org/sources/ . Or 
download libvirt source via git:
git clone git://libvirt.org/libvirt.git

Configuration
Libvirt is built by 
GNU build system.

Change to libvirt source directory.
Generate automake/autoconf scripts: ./autogen.sh
Run configure script to finish configuration before compilation: 
./configureTo use customized configuration options, run ./configure --help to get all 
the configuration options and influential environment variables.

Make
Build libvirt by make. Run 
make command by your purpose:

build libvirt project: make
check the code syntax only: make syntax-check
build libvirt and run unit tests: make check
build libvirt and its rpm packages make rpm

Installation
For rpm target files, install and uninstall them by rpm. The rpm files are in 
~/rpmbuild/RPMS/x86_64/.To install target files by make, run sudo make install in the code directory. 
To uninstall them, run sudo make uninstall.
Build by build system of distributions
Different linux distributions integrate the above processes into their build 
script and build libvirt by their build system. The following is the build script 
and build system of major linux distributions.

rhel/centos/fedora: build processes defined by 
spec file and built by 
rpmbuild
debian/ubuntu: build processes defined by 
control and rules file, 
built by debuild
arch linux: build processes defined by 
PKGBUILD file and built by 
asp
gentoo linux: build processes defined by 
ebuild file 
and built by
ebuild

dir-struct.html.title: Directory Structure
dir-struct.html.body:
TreeviewCopyright © aleen42 all right reserved, powered by aleen42
Directory Structure

schema




Directory Structure
Check libvirt code directory after download. There are following sub-directory 
in libvirt root directory:

build-aux: The autoconf auxiliary directory.
docs: Include the documents of libvirt and libvirt relax-ng 
schema. The former could be seen on libvirt org site.
The later is used for libvirt xml validation, such as virt-xml-validate.
example: This directory contains libvirt API usage examples.
gnulib: The GNU Portability Library. 
A library that libvirt relies on.
include: Libvirt public header files.
m4: GNU M4, a Unix macro processor, is a 
dependency of GNU autoconf.
po: GetText related files, they are 
used for internationalization and localization.
src: The libvirt core library codes.
tests: Libvirt unit test files.
tools: The codes libvirt supplementary programs, such as virsh, 
virsh shell completion, 
libvirt-guests service, 
libvirt wireshark dissector, 
libvirt-nss, 
virt-admin, 
virt-login-shell, 
virt-host-validate, 
virt-pki-validate, 
virt-xml-validate, 
virt-sanlock-cleanup.

schema
Libvirt use xml to record or manage resources, including domain, 
domain snapshot, nodedev, secret, storagevol, capability, 
interface, nwfilter, nwfilterbinding, network.The relax-ng schema files define the format of libvirt xml
